{"bgColorIndex":0,"note":"Thoughts\n\ntoday I finally got to visit Matisse in Morocco this was my dream that came true after so many years of wait our tour guide agreed to take us to the Grand Hotel Philadelphia and we got our way through the hotel into the room number 35 where I finally got to enter into the room from where Matisse painted some of his iconic paintings in Morocco when the waiter or like the assistant from the hotel he was dressed in the French Moroccan uniform opened the window and I took the look outside of the painting that Mattis has done from those point of views it was an experience that couldn't be forget forgotten it's still feels that the time has frozen and a painting had captured the incense of how Morocco look like I almost hundred years ago.  then we also visited the surrounding places where in the hotel where they have this iconic grills and that appear on his various paintings after that our tour guide took us to the alleys to the famous gate in Casper it's an entrance with the red light are coming through the door surprisingly there were a couple of more open people sitting there in the exact same place where he has sketched in a person sitting in his painting the entrance to Casper and lastly we stumbled upon this green Church that was freshly painted and I was it was astoundingly beautiful and I didn't know what it was I was so mesmerized and then our tour guide said that that painting that is in fact where the Matisse has painted his third painting late marble am and it's a beautiful building we actually saw the place where he sat and painted that that mosque it's possible to literally follow his footsteps in the end I would say to exact spots even after 100 years we can actually walk through his footsteps and see where he did all those paintings and most famous work and the vibrancy of the light and the colors is hard to imagine without experiencing it okay usually it's there yeah yeah I'll look and see you on the app if I can find it but if you look and you know just as well as I do and where it normally is if it's not there then you know you know\n\n\nHere are more details for each pic. \n\nPictures \nMorocco 4 and 6 \nMatisse Moosque - This iconic mosque caught by eye as it freshly painted on that day and there was somehting about it. Soon I realized that Matisse had sat in the same corner we stood and painted the same mosque. \n\nMorocco 7 Here is iconic place where he painted the morning sunrise the door and there is some person sitting there just like the one in his paining.\n\nMorocco 8 and 9 - Loved these architectural details. \n\nMorocco 10\nWe visited Ibnbatuta’s resting place - the first travel blogger in the world.\n\n\nMorocco 11. Hotel view from Matisse’s iconic hotel room \n\nMorocco 13 14 18 iconic grill patterns Matisse used in his paintings. they were stunnin gin real life.\n\nMorocco 15 The windows - I ahve now words. \n\nMorocco 16 - the room where he stayed. a true pilgrimage.\n\nMorocco 17 me in front of the hotel \n\nMorocco 5 a snakecharmer - I will probably use him in my new artwork. He modeled for me for a fee. But he was ready an very photogenic. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","textColorIndex":1}